Title : Erna Weill
Text : [[File:Erna Weill (5483044371).jpg|thumb|Erna Weill]]
'''Erna Weill''' (1904-1996) was an American German-Jewish sculptor known for her busts of 20th-century persons, in particular civil rights figures.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22507137.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140611135309/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22507137.html | dead-url=yes | archive-date=2014-06-11 | title=ERNA WEILL, NOTED TEANECK SCULPTOR | work=Bergen Record | date=1996-04-30 | accessdate=4 May 2014 | author=Markowitz, Michael}}</ref>

Born Erna Helft in [[Frankfurt]], [[Germany]], she studied sculpture with Helene von Beckerath, a student of [[Auguste Rodin]], at [[Goethe University Frankfurt]].<ref name=findaid>[http://findingaids.cjh.org/?pID=192289 Michael Aldinger, ''Guide to the Papers of Erna Weill (1904-1966), 1914-1971'' New York: Leo Baeck Institute/Center of Jewish History, 2007.]</ref> In 1933, a course with Martin Buber in Frankfurt inspired her to pursue Jewish themes in her work.<ref name="Levenson2012">{{cite book|author=Alan T. Levenson|title=The Wiley-Blackwell History of Jews and Judaism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KgJtcvs7ObAC&pg=PT379|date=12 March 2012|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-23293-4|page=379}}</ref> She married a chemist, Ernst Weill.

In 1936, the family fled Germany first to Switzerland and then to the United States, settling eventually in [[Teaneck, New Jersey]].  She continued her work of busts of famous people, many from the [[Civil Rights Movement]] and of Jewish themes.  In addition she taught in New York City public schools and had her own art school.<ref name=findaid/>

